  "body": [
    "There is little information known regarding the life of Tilly Bai Ji. Originally from the Sindh province of Pakistan, she moved to Bombay following the partition. Bhai Harbans Singh Suraj (UK) recounted that she performed Kirtan regularly in Ulhas Nagar and his father, Sant Ajit Singh Ji accompanied her on tabla many times. In her article ‘Listening to Female Voices in Sikh Kirtan’, Gurminder Kaur Bhogal has written that Tilly Bai recorded for Deutsche Gramophone under the Polydor label, possibly during the late 60s to 70s. Below is an excerpt from her article with regards to Tilly Bai.",
    "‘Chetna hai to chet lai’ presents a wholly pared-down texture where a predominant melody in raag Tilang-Kafi is lightly accompanied by a simple metric pattern provided by the dholak (in dadra) and a barely audible doubling of the melody in the harmonium. The musical interludes are kept to a minimum and Tilly Bai’s treatment of raag is simple and refined with barely a nod towards melodic embellishment. Unlike any of the other kirtaniye heard here, Tilly Bai’s commitment to a slow tempo allows for a deliberate enunciation of the words, unencumbered by taans and other such ornamental gestures; as she ponders over the poetry and semantics of every phrase, we are invited to do the same.",
    "Till Bai visited Malaysia in 1965 and some of the recordings available below were made then.  If anyone has a photo or more recordings of Tilly Bai Ji to share, please contact us."
  ],
